{"id":"1604.05068","submitter":"Domenico Ditto","authors":"Adriano Orefice, Raffaele Giovanelli, Domenico Ditto","title":"Beyond quasi-optics: an exact approach to self-diffraction, reflection\n  and finite-waist focusing of matter wave trajectories","comments":"10 pages (double column), 13 figures, slight text corrections","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The \"main road\" open by de Broglie's and Schroedinger's discovery of matter\nwaves and of their eigen-functions branched off, as is well known, into\ndifferent \"sub-routes\". The most widely accepted one is Standard Quantum\nMechanics (SQM), interpreting the time-dependent Schroedinger equation as the\nbasic evolution law of a wave-packet which represents the simultaneous\nprobabilistic permanence of a particle in its full set of eigenstates. Another\n\"sub-route\" is offered by Bohm's Mechanics, able to reproduce the same results\nof SQM, while interpreting the stream-lines of the probability current density\nas the \"quantum trajectories\" of the moving particles. Reminding that the\nso-called quasi-optical approximation represents a standard mathematical\ntechnique allowing a ray-based treatment of wave-like features, we present here\nan exact wave-mechanical \"sub-route\", based on the observation that the\ntime-independent Schroedinger equation may be treated, bypassing any\nquasi-optical approximation, in terms of a Hamiltonian set of rays mutually\ncoupled by an energy-dependent function (which we call \"Wave Potential\")\nencoded in the very structure of any Helmholtz-like equation. These rays lend\nthemselves to be interpreted as the exact wave-dynamical trajectories and\nmotion laws of classical-looking point-particles associated with the de\nBroglie-Schroedinger matter waves. The role of the Wave Potential, acting\nperpendicularly to the momentum of the moving particles, is to \"pilot\" them\nwithout any energy exchange: a property which isn't shared by the well-known\n\"Quantum Potential\" of the Bohmian theory, involving the entire spectrum of\npossible eigen-energies of a wave-packet. This property turns out to allow the\nnumerical computation of the particle trajectories, which we perform and\ndiscuss here for particles piloted by the Wave Potential in many different and\nsignificant force-fields.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 18 Apr 2016 10:19:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 31 May 2016 20:42:44 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 2 Aug 2016 09:40:20 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 24 Sep 2016 14:37:02 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 18 Nov 2016 13:29:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-21"}
{"id":"1604.05069","submitter":"Jasson Vindas","authors":"Gregory Debruyne and Jasson Vindas","title":"Complex Tauberian theorems for Laplace transforms with local\n  pseudofunction boundary behavior","comments":"30 pages","journal-ref":"J. Anal. Math. 138 (2019), 799-833","doi":"10.1007/s11854-019-0045-3","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CV math.CA math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We provide several Tauberian theorems for Laplace transforms with local\npseudofunction boundary behavior. Our results generalize and improve various\nknown versions of the Ingham-Fatou-Riesz theorem and the Wiener-Ikehara\ntheorem. Using local pseudofunction boundary behavior enables us to relax\nboundary requirements to a minimum. Furthermore, we allow possible null sets of\nboundary singularities and remove unnecessary uniformity conditions occurring\nin earlier works; to this end, we obtain a useful characterization of local\npseudofunctions. Most of our results are proved under one-sided Tauberian\nhypotheses; in this context, we also establish new boundedness theorems for\nLaplace transforms with pseudomeasure boundary behavior. As an application, we\nrefine various results related to the Katznelson-Tzafriri theorem for power\nseries.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 18 Apr 2016 10:19:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 11 Nov 2016 17:39:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-22"}
